   "source": [
    "## Task 3: Bias in health data\n",
    "**Example** Optum Health Risk Prediction Algorithm Bias (2019)\n",
    "\n",
    "**What happened?** In 2019, a study was published in the journal Science detailing racial biases within a commercial health algorithm most commonly used by organizations around the country, such as hospitals and insurance companies. The algorithm was being employed to locate the high-risk population that could benefit from health care management programs. However, the algorithm did not use race as an actual variable in its decision-making. Instead, access to medical care was factored in as measured by costs spent on healthcare overall. Because historically Black Americans have less access to medical care and lower healthcare expenditures, the algorithm underestimated their risk for illness. As a result, the black patients were less likely to receive additional care attention. It was estimated by researchers that correcting this bias could boost the percentage of Black patients considered for the high-risk care programs from 17.7% to 46.5%.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What could have been done to prevent it?** Using clinical indicators (disease burden) in place of cost as a proxy for need, testing the algorithm with different races before deployment, and involving public health experts in the process of development."
   ]
  },
