    "## Task 4: Anonymization of health data\n",
    "**Example** In the 1990s, the Massachusetts Group Insurance Commission published a large dataset comprising hospital visit records for state employees. The data were deemed \"anonymized\" through the re-moval of apparent identifiers like names and Social Security numbers. But researcher Latanya Sweeney was able to show that the dataset could be re-identified if linked with publicly available voter registration records. Using only ZIP code, birth date, and sex, she was able to re-identify the medical records of then–Governor William Weld. This case showed that simple removal of direct identifiers is insufficient to guarantee privacy.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Description of technique** State relied mainly on data masking, which means the removal of direct identifiers. However, to avoid the issues they faced later on they could have applied generalization provided for items such as broader age groups or aggregation of data."
   ]
